\begin_layout Standard
To fight soaring health care costs and simultaneously increase the quality
 of health care, many researchers are turning to the technologies of robotics
 and intelligent systems to find solutions.
 Over the last decade, there has been an explosion of robotic applications
 in health services.
 The Food and Drug Administration, who reviews data on the safety and effectiven
ess of robotic software and hardware, estimates that 36,600 robotic surgeries
 were done in 2005, up nearly 50 percent from 2004 [ref?].
 Analysts predict the figure will grow at a similar rate as the general
 public becomes informed about the advantages of robotically assissted surgeries
 [ref?].
 Beyond surgical applications 
