\begin_layout Standard
Given the increasing adoption of robotics technology in health care, is
 there reason for concern? There are in fact two reasons.
 The first involves the safety associated with autonomous robots.
 According to FDA records, current commercial surgical robotic systems have
 not caused a patient undue injury [ref].
 However, the reason for this good fortune is not necessarily due to exceptional
 safety measures, even though current systems do employ an impressive array
 of stop-gaps and safety measures.
 Rather current surgical robotic systems are safe due to the design of their
 control system.
 Similar to a vehicle or airplane, current robotic systems are based on
 what called a human-in-the-loop control system.
 They are not autonomous and only move by real-time commands sent by a surgeon.
 Similar to non-robotically assisted surgeries, this control methodology
 simply responds to the surgeon's actions as if they were the surgeon's
 own hands.
 Future systems, however, will yield more autonomous control to the robotic
 system.
 Starting with routine tasks such as suturing, future systems may be capable
 of completeing full procedures [ref].
 Early indications of this trend already exist.
